column1: Estimate commit entropy
column9: Team L1 – Learning From Heterogeneous Developer Data
column26:
How much a developer would change in a file per commit that changes it can be a relevant metric. For example, if a developer only makes small changes in a file, he most likely is not implementing a new feature but doing maintenance work. The goal is figuring out which files a developer is most familiar with to estimate if this developer would be a good choice for tasks regarding a file. This metric could also be used as basis for other metrics, for example if large changes are estimated in a file with a comparatively low amount of lines, this could suggest a problem (file requiring a rewrite for each change)

While a simple version of this could be achieved with statistical approach, using machine learning will enable the usage of multiple inputs that change the estimated entropy.

column1: Fetching related incidents/bugs similar to a new assigned incident
column9: Team L1 – Learning From Heterogeneous Developer Data
column26:
Usually when a developer is assigned a task/incident/bug for which he has no idea how to resolve. The developer tries to find older similar incidents which have been solved because most of the time bugs are in that area of code base.

Build a system which will try to find similar related incidents/bugs. I guess this can be achieved by applying NLP models of  text similarity.

Future scope: We can extend it for finding any related discussions that have taken place related to those solved incidents in Slack.

column1: Estimate incident delivery time based on other incidents
column9: Team L1 – Learning From Heterogeneous Developer Data
column26:
* At the beginning of a project, if a person doesn’t have any experience with such an incident, but the project manager wants to know how much time does the person needs to finish this task.

 * Estimate how long it would take for a developer to complete an incident based on how long other developers took to complete similar projects previously
 * Using ML and NLP models to predict the time estimation for the task based on feature engineering on Jira data.

column1: Jira - Recommendation System: Finding developers who has previously worked on related incidents/bugs
column9: Team L1 – Learning From Heterogeneous Developer Data
column26:
Usually in support providing companies, all the raised bugs/incidents are first assigned to a manager who then allocates them to a correct developer.


Making use of NLP and finding the similarity between the bugs/incidents reported. A recommender system can be developed where we can use pre-trained NLP model like BERT which can help us find incidents/bugs similarity which could be further used in suggesting developers who had previously worked on similar types of bugs/incidents.

column1: Make use of ML and analyze an individual performance
column9: Team L1 – Learning From Heterogeneous Developer Data
column26:
Make use of available data from Github, Slack, Confluence and Jira and evaluate individual performance using ML and NLP.  Parameters which we can use:
 # Number of incidents/Bugs/Stories assigned to the person.
 # Average time taken by the individual to complete those incidents.
 # How active a person is on tools like slack, github, jira.
 # Number of code reviews done by the person.
 # Number of meetings the person is part off.
 # Number of lines of code written by the individual.
 # Number of documentation the person is part off.
